, fare well; make fast the doore;

   〈…〉

Marry, I say, Sir, that neuer any errour came yet vnaccompanied;
and that one inconuenience is the cause of another,
and the doore that opens vnto many.

Cease (good Sir) this vaine and idle humour;


for my eares are tyred with attention, and the Girdle almost worne
out with your often handling.

It is a concealed fire; a pleasing wound; a sauoury poyson;
a sweet bitternesse; a delightfull griefe; a cheerfull torment;
a sweet, yet cruell hurt; and a gentle death.

I stand better; for I haue bound my Sword and
Buckler both together, that they may not fall from me when I run;
and haue clapt my Caske in the cape of my cloake.

Ay, my Cousin! my deare Loue, Sempronio and Parmeno
are now no more; they liue not; they are no longer of this world;
dead, alasse they are dead.
